{
  "text": "There exist many studies in the literature [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] for identification based on dental radiographs. The Automated Dental Identification System in [CITATION_4] isolates the teeth using the integral intensity projection method and it is accepted as the pioneer in terms of the tooth isolation approach. In [CITATION_5] , the snake method is employed to isolate the teeth in advance of using the integral intensity projection to determine the initial contours. These two studies are tested on bitewing images. In [CITATION_6] , the same method in [CITATION_7] ) is used for tooth isolation before applying the Bayesian rule to determine the tooth contours. It is tested on both bitewing and panoramic images; but, the system is semi-automatic. The system in [CITATION_8] eliminates the inaccurate segmentation lines using the dental pulp which is also utilized in [CITATION_9] instead of the gaps between the teeth for separating the adjacent teeth. In [CITATION_10] , the SVM classifier runs with several geometrical tooth features to classify a tooth. The tooth identification is completed after labeling the teeth according to a particular pattern. The system is tested only on bitewing images. In [CITATION_11] , the fusion of three SVM classifiers are used for tooth classification and the Markov chain model is used for labeling. The system is tested on a few panoramic dental radiographs.",
